<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	ws-curves.ptx
	Section 1 (Functions, Vectors, and Vector Fields), worksheet 5:
	Curves and Vector-Valued Functions.

	Ported from the Beamer deck 01_04_Curves.tex (in
	source/notes/latex/, functions-vectors folder):
	parametric curves, parametrizing lines/segments, the derivative
	as velocity, and arclength). Book concepts tracked from
	sec_vvf / sec_vvf_calc / sec_tan_norm; example equations are NOT
	reused from the deck or the book.

	Authored to the SHARED worksheet conventions
	(checklists/worksheet-conventions.md): paired component="stu"/"key"
	reading checks and exercises; one True/False misconception check; one
	read-along TikZ figure; one modern application. Standard notation
	(macros from source/bookends/docinfo.ptx); no new macros.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-curves">
	<title>Curves and Vector-Valued Functions</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>Parametrize a curve given as an intersection of surfaces, and parametrize lines and line segments.</li>
			<li>Write a curve as a vector-valued function <m>\vr(t)</m> and describe its orientation.</li>
			<li>Differentiate a vector-valued function to obtain the velocity (tangent) vector.</li>
			<li>Compute the arclength of a space curve with <m>s = \int_a^b \norm{\vr'(t)}\,dt</m>.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: Curves as vector-valued functions
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>I. A curve is a vector-valued function.</term></p>

		<p>
			A curve in space traced out by a single <term>parameter</term>
			<m>t</m> is described by a <term>vector-valued function</term>
			<md>
				\vr(t) = [x(t),\,y(t),\,z(t)] = x(t)\vi + y(t)\vj + z(t)\vk .
			</md>
			As <m>t</m> runs over its interval, the tip of <m>\vr(t)</m>
			sweeps out the curve. Choosing a parametrization does more than
			name the points: it also fixes a direction of travel, called the
			curve's <term>orientation</term>.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 1 -->
		<p component="stu">
			A curve traced by one parameter is described by a
			<fillin characters="8"/>-valued function
			<m>\vr(t) = [x(t),y(t),z(t)]</m>. Choosing a parametrization also
			gives the curve an <fillin characters="12"/> <nbsp/>(a direction of
			travel).
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			A curve traced by one parameter is described by a
			<m>\underline{\textbf{vector}}</m>-valued function
			<m>\vr(t) = [x(t),y(t),z(t)]</m>. Choosing a parametrization also
			gives the curve an <m>\underline{\textbf{orientation}}</m> (a
			direction of travel).
		</p>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: Parametrizing curves
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>II. Parametrizing curves.</term></p>

		<p>
			A few reliable strategies: (i) if the curve is given by two
			equations, solve for two coordinates in terms of the third and
			let <m>t</m> be that third coordinate; (ii) for a circle or a
			curve on a cylinder <m>x^2+y^2=a^2</m>, let <m>t</m> be the polar
			angle, <m>x=a\cos t</m>, <m>y=a\sin t</m>; (iii) for a
			<term>line</term> through a point <m>P</m> parallel to a vector
			<m>\vv</m>, march from <m>P</m> in the direction <m>\vv</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 2 -->
		<p component="stu">
			A line through the point <m>P</m> parallel to the vector
			<m>\vv</m> is parametrized by <m>\vr(t) = </m>
			<fillin characters="10"/>. For the <em>segment</em> from
			<m>P</m> to <m>Q</m>, take <m>\vr(t) = P + t(Q-P)</m> with
			<m>t</m> restricted to <fillin characters="8"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			A line through the point <m>P</m> parallel to the vector
			<m>\vv</m> is parametrized by
			<m>\vr(t) = \underline{\textbf{P + t\vv}}</m>. For the
			<em>segment</em> from <m>P</m> to <m>Q</m>, take
			<m>\vr(t) = P + t(Q-P)</m> with <m>t</m> restricted to
			<m>\underline{\textbf{[0,1]}}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Parametrize the curve of intersection of the cylinder
					<m>x^2+y^2 = 9</m> and the plane <m>z = y</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Parametrize the curve of intersection of the cylinder
					<m>x^2+y^2 = 9</m> and the plane <m>z = y</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The cylinder has radius <m>3</m>, so let <m>t</m> be the
					polar angle: <m>x = 3\cos t</m>, <m>y = 3\sin t</m>. The
					plane forces <m>z = y = 3\sin t</m>. Thus
					<md>
						\vr(t) = [\,3\cos t,\; 3\sin t,\; 3\sin t\,],
						\qquad t \in [0,2\pi].
					</md>
					(The shadow in the <m>xy</m>-plane is the circle of radius
					<m>3</m>; the plane <m>z=y</m> tilts that circle into an
					ellipse in space.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Parametrize the line through the points
					<m>P = (1,0,2)</m> and <m>Q = (3,4,-1)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Parametrize the line through the points
					<m>P = (1,0,2)</m> and <m>Q = (3,4,-1)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					A direction vector is
					<m>\vv = Q - P = [\,2,\,4,\,-3\,]</m>. Marching from
					<m>P</m>,
					<md>
						\vr(t) = P + t\vv = [\,1+2t,\; 4t,\; 2-3t\,],
						\qquad t \in \R.
					</md>
					(Restricting to <m>t\in[0,1]</m> would give just the
					segment from <m>P</m> to <m>Q</m>.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: The derivative as velocity
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>III. The derivative is the velocity vector.</term></p>

		<p>
			A vector-valued function is differentiated one component at a
			time:
			<md>
				\vr'(t) = [\,x'(t),\; y'(t),\; z'(t)\,].
			</md>
			Thinking of <m>\vr(t)</m> as the position of a moving particle,
			<m>\vr'(t)</m> is its <term>velocity</term>. Geometrically the
			velocity is <term>tangent</term> to the curve and points in the
			direction of increasing <m>t</m>; its magnitude
			<m>\norm{\vr'(t)}</m> is the particle's <term>speed</term>.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 3 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The derivative <m>\vr'(t) = [x'(t),y'(t),z'(t)]</m> is the
			<fillin characters="9"/> <nbsp/>vector; geometrically it is
			<fillin characters="8"/> <nbsp/>to the curve, and its magnitude
			<m>\norm{\vr'(t)}</m> is the <fillin characters="6"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The derivative <m>\vr'(t) = [x'(t),y'(t),z'(t)]</m> is the
			<m>\underline{\textbf{velocity}}</m> vector; geometrically it is
			<m>\underline{\textbf{tangent}}</m> to the curve, and its
			magnitude <m>\norm{\vr'(t)}</m> is the
			<m>\underline{\textbf{speed}}</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="ws-curves-fig-tangent">
			<caption>The velocity <m>\vr'(t)</m> is tangent to the curve at
				<m>\vr(t)</m>, pointing the way the particle is heading.</caption>
			<image width="55%">
				<shortdescription>A curved path in the plane with the position vector drawn from the origin to a point P on the curve, and the velocity vector drawn as an arrow tangent to the curve at P.</shortdescription>
				<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1,>=stealth]
	% axes
	\draw[->] (-0.3,0) -- (5,0) node[anchor=north] {$x$};
	\draw[->] (0,-0.3) -- (0,3.6) node[anchor=east] {$y$};
	% the curve r(t)
	\draw[very thick, blue, smooth] plot coordinates
		{(0.3,0.25) (1,0.45) (1.8,0.85) (2.6,1.5) (3.3,2.35) (3.9,3.25)};
	\node[blue] at (4.05,3.0) {$\vr(t)$};
	% point P on the curve
	\coordinate (P) at (2.6,1.5);
	\fill (P) circle (1.7pt);
	\node[anchor=north west] at (P) {$P=\vr(t)$};
	% position vector from origin to P (dashed)
	\draw[dashed, gray, ->] (0,0) -- (P);
	% velocity (tangent) vector at P
	\draw[very thick, red, ->] (P) -- (3.6,2.55);
	\node[red, anchor=south west] at (3.2,2.2) {$\vr'(t)$};
	\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vr(t) = [\,e^{t},\; t^2,\; \cos t\,]</m>. Find
					<m>\vr'(t)</m> and the velocity <m>\vr'(0)</m> at
					<m>t=0</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vr(t) = [\,e^{t},\; t^2,\; \cos t\,]</m>. Find
					<m>\vr'(t)</m> and the velocity <m>\vr'(0)</m> at
					<m>t=0</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Differentiate each component:
					<md>
						\vr'(t) = [\,e^{t},\; 2t,\; -\sin t\,].
					</md>
					At <m>t=0</m>, <m>\vr'(0) = [\,e^{0},\,0,\,-\sin 0\,] = [\,1,\,0,\,0\,]</m>:
					at that instant the particle is moving in the direction of
					the positive <m>x</m>-axis.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: Arclength
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>IV. Arclength of a curve.</term></p>

		<p>
			To measure the length of a curve, add up many
			<q>small</q> distances <m>ds</m> along it. Since distance equals
			rate times time, a small distance is the speed times a small
			change in <m>t</m>: <m>ds = \norm{\vr'(t)}\,dt</m>. Integrating
			over the parameter interval,
			<md>
				s = \int_C ds = \int_a^b \norm{\vr'(t)}\,dt .
			</md>
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 4 -->
		<p component="stu">
			A small piece of arclength is <m>ds = </m>
			<fillin characters="8"/> <m>\,dt</m>, so the length of the curve
			for <m>a\le t\le b</m> is <m>s = </m> <fillin characters="16"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			A small piece of arclength is
			<m>ds = \underline{\textbf{\norm{\vr'(t)}}}\,dt</m>, so the length
			of the curve for <m>a\le t\le b</m> is
			<m>s = \underline{\textbf{\int_a^b \norm{\vr'(t)}\,dt}}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the length of one turn of the helix
					<m>\vr(t) = [\,3\cos t,\; 3\sin t,\; 4t\,]</m> for
					<m>0 \le t \le 2\pi</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the length of one turn of the helix
					<m>\vr(t) = [\,3\cos t,\; 3\sin t,\; 4t\,]</m> for
					<m>0 \le t \le 2\pi</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The velocity is
					<m>\vr'(t) = [\,-3\sin t,\; 3\cos t,\; 4\,]</m>, so the
					speed is constant:
					<md>
						\norm{\vr'(t)} = \sqrt{9\sin^2 t + 9\cos^2 t + 16}
						= \sqrt{9 + 16} = 5.
					</md>
					Therefore
					<md>
						s = \int_0^{2\pi} 5 \, dt = 10\pi .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the length of one turn of the helix
					<m>\vr(t) = [\,5\cos t,\; 5\sin t,\; 12t\,]</m> for
					<m>0 \le t \le 2\pi</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the length of one turn of the helix
					<m>\vr(t) = [\,5\cos t,\; 5\sin t,\; 12t\,]</m> for
					<m>0 \le t \le 2\pi</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Here <m>\vr'(t) = [\,-5\sin t,\; 5\cos t,\; 12\,]</m> and
					<md>
						\norm{\vr'(t)} = \sqrt{25\sin^2 t + 25\cos^2 t + 144}
						= \sqrt{25 + 144} = \sqrt{169} = 13,
					</md>
					so <m>s = \displaystyle\int_0^{2\pi} 13\,dt = 26\pi</m>.
					(The <m>5</m>-<m>12</m>-<m>13</m> right triangle keeps the
					speed a whole number.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 5: A misconception, an application, and looking ahead
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>V. A caution and an application.</term></p>

		<!-- misconception check: single exercise, solution instructor-only -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-curves-tf-speed">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<alert>True or False.</alert> For a moving particle, the
					speed <m>\norm{\vr'(t)}</m> is the same as
					<m>\dfrac{d}{dt}\norm{\vr(t)}</m>, the rate of change of its
					distance from the origin. Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					<term>False.</term> <m>\norm{\vr'(t)}</m> measures how fast
					the particle moves <em>along its path</em>;
					<m>\frac{d}{dt}\norm{\vr(t)}</m> measures how fast its
					<em>distance from the origin</em> changes. For uniform
					circular motion <m>\vr(t) = [\cos t,\sin t,0]</m> the speed
					is <m>\norm{\vr'(t)} = 1</m> (the particle is moving), yet
					<m>\norm{\vr(t)} = 1</m> is constant, so
					<m>\frac{d}{dt}\norm{\vr(t)} = 0</m>. The two agree only
					when the motion is directly toward or away from the origin.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>An application.</term></p>

		<!-- application (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A helical wheelchair ramp winds exactly once around a
					cylindrical tower of radius <m>3</m> meters while rising a
					total of <m>4\pi</m> meters. Using <m>t\in[0,2\pi]</m> for
					the single turn, a parametrization is
					<m>\vr(t) = [\,3\cos t,\; 3\sin t,\; 2t\,]</m>. How long is
					the ramp?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A helical wheelchair ramp winds exactly once around a
					cylindrical tower of radius <m>3</m> meters while rising a
					total of <m>4\pi</m> meters. Using <m>t\in[0,2\pi]</m> for
					the single turn, a parametrization is
					<m>\vr(t) = [\,3\cos t,\; 3\sin t,\; 2t\,]</m>. How long is
					the ramp?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					As <m>t</m> goes from <m>0</m> to <m>2\pi</m> the height
					<m>z = 2t</m> rises from <m>0</m> to <m>4\pi</m>, as
					required. The velocity is
					<m>\vr'(t) = [\,-3\sin t,\; 3\cos t,\; 2\,]</m>, so
					<md>
						\norm{\vr'(t)} = \sqrt{9\sin^2 t + 9\cos^2 t + 4}
						= \sqrt{13},
					</md>
					and the length is
					<md>
						s = \int_0^{2\pi} \sqrt{13}\, dt = 2\pi\sqrt{13}
						\approx 22.65 \text{ meters}.
					</md>
					(Notice this exceeds the <m>4\pi \approx 12.57</m> meters
					of pure rise <ndash/> the winding adds real distance,
					which is why ramps are gentler to climb than stairs.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<p>
				<alert>Looking ahead.</alert> We now have curves in hand as
				vector-valued functions, together with their velocity and
				length. Next we sharpen the geometry: how a curve
				<term>bends</term> (curvature) and the moving frame of
				tangent and normal vectors it carries. From there the course
				turns to <term>vector fields</term> and to integrating along
				curves <ndash/> the line integrals at the heart of vector
				analysis.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>

</worksheet>
